message: Can't you read? Where you dropped on your head as a kid? The source says that the Vilayat Galgaycho played a "crucial role" In the Nazran raid. You claimes that if I cited the source you'd let it stay, and after I did exactly that, you used racism to deny my claim. I'm not even ingush you racist, I'm Chechen. Nobody doubts that most fighters were Chechen, but ingush played a big enough role for it to be a ingush Chechen seperatist victory

Listen here you idiot, I suggest you watch your mouth before using racism to give your delusional claims a basis. You asked for a source, I gave you a source, and know yourusing racism to deny a claim with evidence
As you wanted. Nobody tries to argue about what who made up the larger part of the force, but it's still a chechen ingush seperatist victory

"The group played a key role in the 2004 Nazran raid, an important event which helped to escalate the low-level Ingush insurgency since 2002 into the increasing unrest" - wiki article "Vilayat galgaycho" you literally proved yourself wrong by stating 20-30 ingush took part, which automatically means it was a chechen-ingush victory
The 13th century ist between 1201-1300. also its incorrect to say it lasted "32 years" As it wasn't just one invasion
I mean maybe chechens were more, but it was still a seperatist victory no? Also the CRI did not exist by then
That's why it's called pyrrhic victory.
From first Mongol invasion to third
No it did not, Simsir did not exist back then
/* Battle of Sadoy-Lam */Not to mention the fact that feudalism continued well into the 15th/16th century, or how else did Khasi II and Khour II rise to power 100 years after the invasion

/* Third Mongol Invasion */No, this was the Durdzuk society ever since the Khazar invasion, not after the timurid one. This fact is also approved by Chechnyas most respected historian, Amin Tasayev, go check for yourself. There may be a section for that event, but it's important to know if you want to understand the following events (see prince ors, prince botur, battle of Sadoy-Lam)
/* Prelude */It is, actually, as it gives a background on the first Mongol invasion in 1227
Stop changing the numbers without providing sources
/* Mongol Empire */That made up invasion never happened
Ögedei was barely any involved in this war
El Khasi and El Khour were commanders of the dzurdzuk army
